# Promptly - Product Requirements Document (PRD)

**Version:** 1.0  
**Date:** January 4, 2026  
**Product Name:** Promptly  
**Tagline:** Shape learning experience

---

## 1. Executive Summary

### 1.1 Product Overview
Promptly is a web-based application designed to revolutionize prompt engineering by providing a modular, reusable system for creating, managing, and optimizing AI prompts. The platform combines AI-assisted prompt generation with a component library system, enabling users to build sophisticated prompts through both conversational interfaces and visual block composition.

### 1.2 Target Users
- AI/ML engineers and researchers
- Product managers working with AI systems
- Students wanting to learn proper usage of AI tools
- Educators teaching prompt engineering

### 1.3 Core Value Proposition
- **Efficiency:** Reuse proven prompt components across projects
- **Consistency:** Maintain standardized prompt structures
- **Learning:** Guided prompt creation with AI assistance focusin on step by step creation
- **Collaboration:** Share and discover effective prompt patterns
- **Quality:** Build on tested, refined prompt elements

---

## 2. Product Goals & Success Metrics

### 2.1 User Goals
- Reduce prompt creation time by 60%
- Improve prompt effectiveness through reusable components
- Learn prompt engineering best practices
- Build a personal library of reliable prompt components

## 3. User Personas

### 3.1 Primary Persona: "Alex the AI Engineer"
- **Demographics:** 28-35 years old, Computer Science background
- **Goals:** Create effective prompts quickly, maintain consistency across projects
- **Pain Points:** Starting from scratch each time, forgetting effective patterns
- **Use Case:** Building prompts for production AI applications

### 3.2 Secondary Persona: "Morgan the Content Creator"
- **Demographics:** 25-40 years old, creative professional
- **Goals:** Generate consistent AI content, learn prompt techniques
- **Pain Points:** Uncertainty about prompt quality, inefficient trial-and-error
- **Use Case:** Creating content generation workflows

### 3.3 Tertiary Persona: "Sam the Educator"
- **Demographics:** 30-50 years old, teaching or training background
- **Goals:** Teach prompt engineering, provide students with examples
- **Pain Points:** Need for structured learning resources
- **Use Case:** Creating educational prompt templates

---

## 4. Feature Requirements

### 4.1 Core Features (MVP - Phase 1)

#### 4.1.1 Landing Page
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Clear value proposition and product explanation
- "New Prompt" CTA button
- Navigation to Home, Library(prompts and elements created by users), Templates(basic templates for common use cases)
- User authentication (Sign Up/Login)
- Responsive design with modern aesthetic
- Abstract 3D visual elements (glassmorphism style)

**User Stories:**
- As a new visitor, I want to understand what Promptly does within 5 seconds
- As a returning user, I want quick access to create a new prompt from elements i created before with just little twist depending o use case
- As any user, I want to navigate easily between main sections

#### 4.1.2 AI Chat Assistant ("Chat with Chad")
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Real-time chat interface with Claude API integration
- Constrained to prompt engineering topics only
- Text input field with "Commit to Prompt" action
- Conversation history within session
- Streaming responses for better UX,
- System prompt that enforces domain constraints

**System Prompt Structure:**
```
You are "Chef", a specialized prompt engineering assistant for Promptly.

SCOPE: You ONLY help with:
- Prompt creation and structure
- Prompt engineering techniques (CoT, Few-Shot, ReAct, Tree of Thoughts, etc.)
- Explaining prompt components (like: Task, Actor, Context, Output, Examples)
- Improving and refining prompts
- Suggesting appropriate techniques for user goals

AVAILABLE TECHNIQUES: Chain of Thought, Few-Shot Learning, ReAct, Tree of Thoughts, 
Role Prompting, Constitutional AI, Self-Consistency, Meta-Prompting, and more if available from reliable web sources.

BLOCK TYPES YOU HELP CREATE:depending on the use case. 

Chef is a meta-prompt creation assistant that guides users step-by-step through building prompts using various techniques.
Conversation Flow:

Introduces himself: "Hi! My name is Chef! A meta prompt master."
Asks what LLM will be used (Claude, ChatGPT, etc.)
Asks about the task/project description
Asks which technique to use (TACO, RISEN, Chain of Thought, Multiple Outputs, Tree of Thought, System Prompting)

If user doesn't know, Chef recommends one with a SHORT explanation why


Guides through technique-specific components step-by-step
For each component, Chef proposes ONE option (max 3 sentences) based on context
User can accept, modify, or provide their own
After completing standard components, asks: "Would you like to add any additional elements? (e.g., examples, constraints, formatting rules)"
Only generates final prompt when user says "generate final prompt"

Communication Style:

Concise and token-efficient (no "Excellent choice!" or unnecessary phrases)
No "Chef:" prefix before responses
Direct and clear
Proposes solutions rather than asking open-ended questions
Keeps conversation understandable but minimal

User Flexibility:

Users can add custom segments at any point (examples, constraints, edge cases, formatting rules, etc.)
Users can request modifications to any component before finalizing
Users can ask Chef to include additional elements specific to their use case

Reference Materials:
Chef has access to XML files containing detailed information about:

TACO & RISEN frameworks
Zero-shot, One-shot, Few-shot, Iterative prompting
Chain of Thought, Multiple Outputs, Tree of Thought
System Prompting, Meta-Prompting
Interview techniques, persona creation, presentation building

Key Rule: Chef uses these references to know WHAT to ask and HOW to structure questions for each technique, especially for complex ones like Chain of Thought (which requires examples with reasoning) or Tree of Thought (which requires multiple paths and evaluation criteria).

Real-Time Prompt Showcase (Right Panel):
As Chef asks questions and proposes options in the chat (left side), the right panel displays a live preview of the prompt being built.
How it works:

Live Proposals: When Chef proposes something (e.g., "Task: Easy-to-use web app that equips the next generation of designers and engineers with the foundational skills for innovation: Prompt Creation!"), it appears in the right panel under the appropriate section (Task, Actor, Context, Output) in a "preview" or "pending" state.
Waiting State: Sections that haven't been filled yet show "Waiting to fill the prompt" in gray/placeholder text.
User Response: When the user accepts, modifies, or provides their own answer in the chat, that section updates in real-time on the right.
Commit to Lock: The "Commit to Prompt" button (or command in chat) locks in that specific element, moving it from "preview" to "confirmed" state. Each element has its own commit action - you don't commit everything at once, but rather commit each component (Task, Actor, Context, Output) separately as you complete them.
Visual Feedback: Committed elements might change color, get a checkmark, or have a different visual state to show they're locked in and approved.

So the flow is:
Chef proposes → Right panel previews → User approves/modifies → User commits that element → Element locks → Move to next component

**Technical Specifications:**
- API: Anthropic Claude API (claude-sonnet-4-20250514)
- Max tokens: 1000 per response
- Temperature: 0.7 for creativity with consistency
- Context window management: Last 10 messages + system prompt
- Error handling: Graceful fallbacks for API failures

**User Stories:**
- As a user, I want to describe my goal and get prompt structure suggestions
- As a beginner, I want explanations of different prompt techniques
- As an advanced user, I want to refine existing prompts with AI assistance

#### 4.1.3 Prompt Builder Interface
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Two-panel layout: Chat (left) + Prompt Builder (right)
- Editable prompt title field ("Name Me!" placeholder)
- Structured block sections(depending on used technique):
  - Task
  - Actor
  - Context
  - Output
  - Examples
- Each block is:
  - Independently editable (rich text)
  - Collapsible/expandable
  - Deletable
  - Reorderable (drag to reposition)
- "Save" button to store prompt in the library
- Markdown support in blocks

**User Stories:**
- As a user, I want to see my prompt structure clearly organized
- As a user, I want to edit any block independently
- As a user, I want my work saved automatically
- As a user, I want to add custom block types beyond the defaults

#### 4.1.4 Block Library Sidebar
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Search functionality (filters blocks by content/tags)
- Categorized view (group by block type)
- Block preview cards showing:
  - Block type badge
  - First 100 characters of content
  - Source prompt name
  - Created date
- Drag and drop to insert into current prompt
- Hover preview with full content
- Infinite scroll or pagination
- Filter by:
  - Block type
  - Date created
  - Source prompt
  - Custom tags

**User Stories:**
- As a user, I want to quickly find and reuse blocks from past prompts
- As a user, I want to preview block content before inserting
- As a user, I want to filter blocks by type or project

#### 4.1.5 Prompt Library (Gallery View)
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Card-based grid layout (responsive)
- Each card displays:
  - Prompt title
  - All constituent blocks (collapsed preview)
  - Color-coded borders per prompt
  - Created/modified date
  - Quick action buttons (Edit, Duplicate, Delete)
- Horizontal carousel navigation (< >)
- "Mixer" button for combining prompts
- Search and filter capabilities
- Sort options:
  - Recently created
  - Recently modified
  - Alphabetical
  - Most used

**User Stories:**
- As a user, I want to see all my saved prompts at a glance
- As a user, I want to quickly duplicate successful prompts
- As a user, I want to organize prompts by project or technique

#### 4.1.6 User Authentication
**Priority:** P0 (Critical)

**Requirements:**
- Email/password authentication
- OAuth options (Google, GitHub)
- Password reset functionality
- Email verification
- Session management
- Secure token storage

**Technical Specifications:**
- Auth provider: Auth0, Supabase Auth, or Clerk
- JWT tokens for API authentication
- Refresh token rotation
- HTTPS only

